name: Tammy Baldwin
content:
As we joined together to raise the #Pride flag above our State Capitol today in recognition of #PrideMonth, let us remember it’s a symbol of fairness – about whether LGBTQ Wisconsinites deserve to be treated just like their family members, their friends, and their neighbors.

It’s about opportunity – about working together to break down barriers so that everyone in Wisconsin has an equal opportunity to dream the same dreams, chase the same ambitions and have the same shot at success.

And it’s about the ongoing march for freedom – the freedom of full equality for the LGBTQ community.

Most of all, it’s about whether the progress Wisconsin has made will continue. Today, we ask ourselves if we will live up to our state motto – “Forward.”

And today, we come together as one community to answer that question – “Yes.”

content:
Today marks the beginning of Pride Month. As we reflect on the more than 50 years of protest and celebration that have brought us to today, let us all renew our commitment to fighting for equal rights for LGBTQ Americans.

We’ve made a lot of progress—but there are still steps we can take to protect the civil rights of everyone in this country. In my view, that starts with passing the Equality Act and enshrining protection from discrimination for LGBTQ Americans in federal law. I will not give up the fight in the Senate until we get the Equality Act passed and signed into law by President Biden.

name: Dan Sullivan
content:
The Interior Department's announcement today suspending leases in the 1002 Area of ANWR goes against the law, facts, the science, and the will of the Native communities on the North Slope. It is nothing more than a naked political move by the Biden administration to pay off its extreme environmental allies. The law is clear: Congress mandated the leasing program in the 1002 Area and required two lease sales within seven years. BLM Alaska’s staff worked tirelessly to develop a comprehensive and durable EIS and leasing program in order to issue the first leases in 2021. The announcement today disregards that fact-based scientific work, as well as the property interests of those who hold these leases, including the State of Alaska. It also utterly disregards BLM scientists and Alaskans from across the political spectrum—Republicans, Democrats, Independents, unions, working families, as well the Alaska Natives who live closest to the area and who fought for decades for the right to allow for the responsible development of the 1002 Area of ANWR in order to strengthen our communities and build a better life for our children.

SULLIVAN.SENATE.GOV
Alaska Delegation, Governor Rebuke Biden Administration For Cancelling Lawful ANWR Leases | U.S. Senator Dan Sullivan of Alaska

name: Susan M. Collins
content:
Congratulations to Capt. Chris Cassidy of York on his retirement following a stellar career that ranged from underwater to outer space!

Over nearly three decades of service in the Navy and at NASA, Chris, a Navy SEAL, was deployed four times, received the bronze star, and participated in three space flights. When he joined Dr. Jessica Meir on the International Space Station last year, it marked the first time in history that two Mainers were in space simultaneously. I was delighted to participate in a Q&A with them on NASA TV so that students and educators could hear about their experiences.

Thank you, Chris, for inspiring countless young Mainers to reach for the stars, achieve their dreams, and serve their country.

https://www.pressherald.com/2021/05/28/maine-astronaut-chris-cassidy-retiring-after-28-years-of-public-service/

name: Christopher A. Coons
content:
This centennial of the Tulsa Race Massacre presents an important opportunity to listen and learn and to recognize those whose lives were lost or irreparably altered by this dark moment in our nation’s history.

In Tulsa, I joined Congresswoman Lisa Blunt Rochester in laying a wreath at the dedication of the prayer wall at the Vernon AME Church in Greenwood in memory of those lost. We saw the basement of the church—where survivors gathered to begin the process of rebuilding Greenwood and reclaiming their lives. It was powerfully moving to see marks of the fire and to hear from members of the congregation about their work and challenges in the city today.

Our pilgrimage concluded with a candlelight vigil in the rain where we joined hundreds of people to stand along Greenwood Avenue – in memory of those whose lives and homes and businesses were destroyed a century ago.

I hope we can all take time to reflect on this history today.

📸 Credit for photos two and three belongs to Cheriss May who helped capture this powerful event for The Faith & Politics Institute

name: Chris Van Hollen
content:
Healing the wounds of racial violence and injustice – past and present – requires action. We must promote equity and enact policies that start to remedy past measures that denied Black communities access to opportunities and wealth-building. That’s why I’m glad to see President Biden announce new action today – as we mark the Tulsa Race Massacre – to address long-standing racial discrimination in housing and to increase the federal government’s investment in small disadvantaged businesses. President Biden also announced further moves to confront inequitable infrastructure through the American Jobs Plan — like reconnecting communities divided by highways and roads — as we’re working to do through the elimination of Baltimore’s Highway to Nowhere. There’s much more work to be done to address the racial wealth gap, but these are important steps in the right direction.

WHITEHOUSE.GOV
FACT SHEET: Biden-Harris Administration Announces New Actions to Build Black Wealth and Narrow the Racial Wealth Gap | The White House

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: On May 31st we celebrate Memorial Day—but there’s another special day of recognition in Alaska that must not go unacknowledged: Katie John Day. Katie John was a widely respected Ahtna Athabascan leader and passionate advocate for Native and civil rights. Katie is remembered for a number of things— a case she championed on behalf of subsistence rights which ensured that generations of Natives to come would be allowed to continue the subsistence way of life in rural Alaska. She was also a champion of teaching and preserving Athabascan culture. In fact, in the 1970s, she helped create the first written alphabet of Ahtna dialect. To honor her contributions to Alaska Natives, I again championed a Senate Resolution that recognized the contributions made by Native women. In this year’s resolution, I added Katie John. Today, I encourage all Alaskans to honor and remember Alaska Native icon, Katie John—a true piece of Alaska’s soul.

content:
June is National Gun Violence Awareness Month.

Thanks to gun safety advocates like my friend, Linda Beigel Schulman, New York is at the forefront of advancing gun safety legislation by closing loopholes in our state gun laws.

On the federal level, we can, and we must, do more. We must work with the Senate to strengthen background checks for gun buyers and close the Charleston and ghost gun loopholes. Lives depend on it.

Every day, more than 300 people are directly impacted by gun violence in the United States. Gun Violence Awareness Month was created to draw attention to this tragic reality and demand life-saving changes.

content: 2021 marks the 50th anniversary of the ratification of the 26th amendment, which gave 18-year-olds the right to vote. Ella Mae Thompson Haddix of Randolph County became the first 18-year-old in the United States registered to vote. U.S. Senator Jennings Randolph had been championing the amendment since World War II saying, “Old enough to die for your country, old enough to vote!” After meeting Ms. Thompson she agreed to go to The Randolph Clerk’s office to be registered. This picture on the steps at the Randolph County Courthouse shows her with the clerk and other elected officials with her original registration form.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content:
Today the Department of the Interior announced it will suspend all oil and gas leases for portions of the non-wilderness Coastal Plain (1002 Area) of the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge (ANWR), pending the outcome of another environmental review. The Biden administration’s actions are not unexpected but are outrageous nonetheless. Suspending leases in Alaska’s 1002 Area is in direct conflict with the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, through which Congress mandates an oil and gas leasing program be established on the non-wilderness Coastal Plain, and ordered at least two lease sales by 2024. In addition, The Act specifically states that the purpose of the 1002 area of ANWR is oil and gas development. The oil and gas leasing program established by the Trump Administration meets the legal mandates required by Congress including imposing a framework with a range of environmental safeguards that are successfully guiding production elsewhere in northern Alaska. This action serves no purpose other than to obstruct Alaska’s economy and put our energy security at great risk. Alaskans are committed to developing our resources responsibly and have demonstrated our ability to do so safely to the world. For more information, follow the link below.

MURKOWSKI.SENATE.GOV
Alaska Delegation, Governor Rebuke Biden Administration For Cancelling Lawful ANWR Leases | U.S. Senator Lisa Murkowski of Alaska

The Maryland congressional delegation today announced nearly $28 million in federal COVID-19 relief funding designed to reduce health disparities by strengthening health equity initiatives in high-risk and underserved communities across the state.

We’ve got to change the way that our country deals with mental health.

My new bipartisan legislation with Sen. John Cornyn will overhaul our national response to behavioral health crises including:

✅24/7 crisis hotlines and call centers
✅mobile crisis services
✅behavioral health urgent care facilities
✅crisis stabilization and observation beds
✅short-term crisis residential options
And coverage for behavioral health crisis services for ALL patients, no matter where they get their health insurance.

There’s a lot to do to address our country’s mental health. Let’s get to work.

name: Ed Perlmutter
content:
I believe highlighting and preserving our Veterans’ stories is one of the many ways to recognize their service and sacrifice for our country. That's why today I'm proud to share the latest Veterans History Project interview conducted by my office. Michael Knight served in the U.S. Marine Corps from November 2005 to April 2011 and is now a PhD student at the Colorado School of Mines. He was interviewed via Zoom by one of our interns during the spring 2021 semester.

Every story collected from a Veteran is a unique and significant piece of history, and I want to thank Michael for his service to our country and for taking the time to share his story.

Watch the full interview with Michael and learn more about the Library of Congress Veterans History Project here --> https://perlmutter.house.gov/constituent-services/veterans-history-project.htm.

content:
Voting for the #WI06 Congressional Art Competition People’s Choice Award ends TODAY at 5 p.m. Official votes are tallied on Facebook, so click the link below to choose!

Congressman Glenn Grothman
May 24 at 3:19 PM ·

Each year, high school students around Wisconsin’s Sixth District submit works of art to the Artistic Discovery Competition. The winner will have his or her artwork displayed in the U.S. Capitol for one year in an exhibit that features winners from other congressional districts across the U.S.

Now, it’s time for you to vote for the People’s Choice Award!

I’ve posted all submissions here. The work of art that received the most “likes” will be declared the People’s Choice Award winner. Voting ends on Tuesday, June 1 at 5 p.m.

I’m so proud of all of the talented young men and women who submitted these beautiful works of art, so make sure to vote for your favorite and forward this post to your family and friends!
